<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>VSphere 9.0 on My Cloudy World</title><link>http://jadenetworksolutions.co.uk/categories/vsphere-9.0/</link><description>Recent content in VSphere 9.0 on My Cloudy World</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><managingEditor>gblake@jadenetworks.co.uk (Gary Blake)</managingEditor><webMaster>gblake@jadenetworks.co.uk (Gary Blake)</webMaster><copyright>Copyright © 2019–2026, Gary Blake; all rights reserved.</copyright><lastBuildDate>Tue, 22 Jul 2025 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="http://jadenetworksolutions.co.uk/categories/vsphere-9.0/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Using VMware.Sdk.Vsphere: Commands for vSphere</title><link>http://jadenetworksolutions.co.uk/post/vcf-90/vcf-90-powercli-vsphere-cmdlets/</link><pubDate>Tue, 22 Jul 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>gblake@jadenetworks.co.uk (Gary Blake)</author><guid>http://jadenetworksolutions.co.uk/post/vcf-90/vcf-90-powercli-vsphere-cmdlets/</guid><description><p>VCF PowerCLI 9.0 now includes a module called<code>VMware.Sdk.Vsphere</code>, this modules contains auto-generated cmdlets to support vSphere Public APIs. Use can use this post as a quick reference guide.</p><h3 id="connecting-to-a-vcenter-instance-with-local-credentials">Connecting to a vCenter Instance with Local Credentials</h3><ol><li><p>Start a PowerShell session.</p></li><li><p>Connect to a vCenter instance using local credentials by running the following command:</p></li></ol><div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"><code class="language-powershell" data-lang="powershell"><span class="line"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="cl"><span class="nb">Connect-VIServer</span><span class="n">-Server</span><span class="nb">sfo-m01</span><span class="n">-vc01</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="py">sfo</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="py">rainpole</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="py">io</span><span class="n">-Username</span><span class="n">administrator</span><span class="nv">@vsphere</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="py">local</span><span class="n">-Password</span><span class="n">VMw</span><span class="nv">@re1</span><span class="p">!</span><span class="n">VMw</span><span class="nv">@re1</span><span class="p">!</span></span></span></code></pre></div><ol><li>Once connected the following information is stored in<code>$global:DefaultVIServer</code>.</li></ol><div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="line"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="cl">Name : sfo-m01-vc01.sfo.rainpole.io</span></span><span class="line"><span class="ln">2</span><span class="cl">Port :<span class="m">443</span></span></span><span class="line"><span class="ln">3</span><span class="cl">User VSPHERE.LOCAL<span class="se">\A</span>dministrator</span></span></code></pre></div><ol start="4"><li>Disconnect from a vCenter instance by running the following command:</li></ol><div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"><code class="language-powershell" data-lang="powershell"><span class="line"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="cl"><span class="nb">Disconnect-VIServer</span><span class="n">-Server</span><span class="nb">sfo-m01</span><span class="n">-vc01</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="py">sfo</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="py">rainpole</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="py">io</span></span></span></code></pre></div><hr><p><strong>NOTE</strong></p></description></item></channel></rss>